I had lunch at Lebanese Taverna with a friend that I havent seen in 15 years. We were the first customers as soon as they opened at noon. We ordered appetizers and drinks everything was great. After we received our appetizers the waiter never returned to our table. Around 130ish (an hour and a half later) We waved down our waiter to ask where our food was and he was like oh you need your check. We are said no we never got our food. We had to get it to go because of time. We didnt get our food until 2pm. We asked could we get a discount on our meal or appetizers for free since we had to wait so long for our food. The waiter and manager denied saying that it wasnt their fault they got too busy, but every other customer that came after us got their food in a timely manner. Also if the waiter would have came to the table at least once to check on us he would have know that we never received our entree. There was a table about 8ft away that he visited 6 times and not once said anything to us.  I do not like to pull the race card but my friend and I were the only African Americans in that restaurant. I bet if we were one of the white customers we wouldnt have been forgotten about and they would have been more apologetic. I honestly felt discriminated against and it was not a good feeling. I will never return to this restaurant I did not enjoy the experience or customer service. It has been almost a week and I still feel some type of way about this.

The hommus is excellent, and so is the pita. Tastes fresh and like it made daily because it doesn’t taste like “hummus” like a lot of of places that get it either pre-made or batch it out. Also got the Chicken Farrouj, the chicken was nice and juicy. The vegetables and the accompanying sauce were bursting with flavor. I also got the chicken curry, prepared expertly. The fattoush salad was great, the pomegranate dressing really set it off.  And finally got the Shawarma Rolls, with labneh were very unique, like a lightly sweet sausage wrapped in pastry. Needless to say between the two of us we only seem to be able to get through about 20% of it haha. So depending on your appetite, and group size the food is plentiful!

To introduce myself first, I am a Lebanese guy who hasn't had a proper Lebanese meal in at least 4 months because of the pandemic. Once someone like me hasn't eaten good food like that for that long... You start to crave it... A little bit.  Anyway! I've eaten tons of Lebanese food back home (and outside of Lebanon, but they were bad). So I've set my standards for this place pretty low, since no place outside the country seems to know how to get things right! We don't put rice in shawarma! No cucumbers (use pickles please), no house salad (hell no!).  But I was pleasantly surprised. Blown away even! This place serves the best (closest to authentic) Lebanese food I've ever had outside Lebanon! Hommos, kibbe, falafel, shawarma, Labneh, fatoush... The list goes on and they were on par with many restaurants I've visited back home (I nearly broke down in tears of joy)!  All the way up to the main course of mixed skewers, things were on point. However, the meat was a little too dry and tough (I'd recommend the chicken/taouck, extra toum! (which means extra garlic back home) ).  The service was great. Very nice people and, despite the pandemic, everything was very organized. Very nice atmosphere and old-school Lebanese music in the background.  In conclusion, I am happy and satisfied. Never thought this place would be this good.  If you want close to authentic Lebanese food, don't hesitate to visit this place! I know I will be back when I start missing home again!

We found the Lebanese Taverna while staying nearby on Baltimore inner harbor waterfront. It was a raucous evening, with a birthday party and seasonal office parties sharing the dining room and bar areas. Our party of two was quickly seated despite arriving sans reservation at the start of the dinnertime rush. Our server, Mehmet, steered us toward the house specialty lamb dishes and he was spot-on! The pulled lamb appetizer, served with fresh breads, could be a meal in itself, but was just right for sharing. Mehmet's mouth-watering description of the lamb chops (more like portioned rack of lamb) had us all-in on the proposition. Four tender chops seasoned and cooked to perfection were accompanied by delicious rice and vegetables. We matched our meals with local beers on draft that made everything just right.

One of our favorite restaurants, loved by the whole family, including the vegan and the unapologetic carnivores alike. My favorite item is the chicken fata (shredded chicken breast on a bed of garlic-butter pita croutons), but ask for a little extra yogurt sauce on the side. Other favorites include nearly all the mezza items (small plates), but especially the artichokes, the arnabeet (cauliflower), and the fatayer trio. The standards -- hummus, baba ghanouj, tabouli, fattoush, kibbe -- are excellent. One of the mezze sampler plates is a good bet that will  give a lot of things to try. But the piece de resistance, the thing you will just adore, is the pita bread, which is freshly baked on the premises and served straight out of the oven.
